│ delete them using DTU.deleteBB(DeadBB). However, the pass only turns     │
│ dead blocks into unreachable (changeToUnreachable) and then removes      │
│ non-feasible edges for executable blocks. It does not guarantee that all │
│ incoming edges to dead blocks are removed before calling deleteBB. As a  │
│ result, DTU.deleteBB is invoked on blocks that still have predecessors,  │
│ triggering the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows:\n-  │
│ Dead blocks identified: \"BasicBlock Dead: loop ... exit\" for           │
│ callee-like functions.\n- changeToUnreachable is applied to the first    │
│ non-PHI instruction of dead blocks.\n- Then removeNonFeasibleEdges runs  │
│ and may rewrite some terminators but focuses on feasible edges from      │
│ analyzed blocks. It doesn't necessarily remove all incoming edges into   │
│ dead blocks.\n- Finally, DTU.deleteBB is called for each DeadBB in       │
│ BlocksToErase without checking pred_empty, which leads to the assertion: │
│ validateDeleteBB's pred_empty check fails.\nThis sequence matches the    │
│ first transformation point and the backtrace and aligns with the         │
│ observed behavior that the block still has predecessors at deletion      │
│ time.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIPSCCP's deletion logic assumes that,  │
│ after changeToUnreachable and edge cleanup, the dead basic blocks will   │
│ be isolated (no predecessors). This is not always the case. SCCP         │
│ solver's removeNonFeasibleEdges only processes br/switch/indirectbr      │
│ terminators for blocks that it decides to change and does so per-block;  │
│ it does not globally ensure all preds are removed for every dead block.  │
│ Consequently, BlocksToErase may still have predecessors when             │
│ DTU.deleteBB is called, violating DTU's precondition. The assertion is   │
│ correct; the pass is attempting an illegal deletion.\n\n4. Proposed Edit │
│ Point(s):\nEdit llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/SCCP.cpp around lines 249-252 to │
│ add a pred_empty check before calling DTU.deleteBB. This keeps deletion  │
│ safe and defers the removal of such blocks to later cleanup passes if    │
│ predecessors remain.\n\nCurrent code:\n  for (BasicBlock *DeadBB :       │
│ BlocksToErase)\n    if (!DeadBB->hasAddressTaken())\n                    │
│ DTU.deleteBB(DeadBB);\n\nProposed change:\n  for (BasicBlock *DeadBB :   │
│ BlocksToErase) {\n    if (DeadBB->hasAddressTaken())\n      continue;\n  │
│ // Only delete blocks that are fully disconnected to respect DTU         │
│ preconditions.\n    if (pred_empty(DeadBB))\n                            │
│ DTU.deleteBB(DeadBB);\n    // Otherwise, keep them with an unreachable   │
│ terminator; later passes will clean up.\n  }\n\nThis ensures we only     │
│ call DTU.deleteBB when the block has no predecessors, satisfying         │
│ validateDeleteBB. It aligns with the intended pipeline: mark dead, make  │
│ unreachable, remove non-feasible edges where possible, and only delete   │
│ blocks when safe.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe fix guards DTU.deleteBB with    │
│ pred_empty to respect DomTreeUpdater's invariants. This prevents the     │
│ assertion and maintains correctness: dead blocks are left with           │
│ unreachable terminators when predecessors still exist, allowing          │
│ subsequent CFG simplification/DCE passes to safely remove them once      │
│ edges are gone. The change is minimal, localized, and consistent with    │
│ DTU's contract."})                                                       │
